The [RecordMetadata][1] object is returned on `KafkaProducer.send` while producing the data into topic

&gt;The send() method is asynchronous. When called it adds the record to a buffer of pending record sends and immediately returns. This allows the producer to batch together individual records for efficiency.

&gt;The producer consists of a pool of buffer space that holds records that haven&#39;t yet been transmitted to the server as well as a background I/O thread that is responsible for turning these records into requests and transmitting them to the cluster. Failure to close the producer after use will leak these resources.

Since the `send` method returns `Future&lt;RecordMetadata&gt;` and result of every record is executed my asynchronous thread, you can add [call back][2] to print the `offset`, `partition` and record information or the exception on failure

      ProducerRecord&lt;byte[],byte[]&gt; record = new 
      ProducerRecord&lt;byte[],byte[]&gt;(&quot;the-topic&quot;, key, value);
      producer.send(myRecord,
               new Callback() {
                   public void onCompletion(RecordMetadata metadata, Exception e) {
                       if(e != null) {
                          e.printStackTrace();
                       } else {
                          System.out.println(&quot;The offset of the record we just sent is: &quot; + metadata.offset());
                       }
                   }
               });


**Note :** While producing the record into Kafka topic, due to the asynchronous mechanism the thread invoking `send` method will be different than the threads executing the `Future&lt;RecordMetadata&gt;` result.

