To answer your question, the [`java.time.LocalDateTime`][2] class may be of help. With it you are able to fetch the current hour of the day on the user&#39;s computer using [`LocalDateTime.now().getHour()`][3]. The method returns the hour in the form of an int with 0 being 12am and 23 being 11pm. I&#39;ve included some sample code below to help you better understand how you could use this to solve your problem

    import java.time.LocalDateTime;
    
    public class Main {
    	
    	public static void main(String[] args) {
    		
    		int[] hourRange = {10, 14}; // Hour range 10am to 2pm
    		
    		// If low range is above high range then swap them
    		if (hourRange[1] &lt; hourRange[0]) {
    			int tmp = hourRange[0];
    			hourRange[0] = hourRange[1];
    			hourRange[1] = tmp;
    		}
    		
    		int currentHour = LocalDateTime.now().getHour(); // Get the current hour in 24 hour time (https://www.onlineconversion.com/date_12-24_hour.htm)
    		boolean lock = currentHour &gt; hourRange[0] &amp;&amp; currentHour &lt; hourRange[1]; // Check if it&#39;s inside of the range. If it is then the bool will be true, otherwise false
